"""Short-form paraphrases part 2 — fills retrieval gaps for short queries that previously missed."""
LESSONS=[
    ('What is Bitcoin?','First cryptocurrency (2009). Decentralized digital cash, peer-to-peer over a blockchain. Mining via Proof of Work; limited supply (21M total); no central authority. Block time ~10 min, ~7 tx/sec. Use cases: store of value (digital gold), payments (slow vs credit cards), hedge against inflation. Created by pseudonymous Satoshi Nakamoto.'),
    ('What is Ethereum?','Blockchain with built-in smart contract scripting (Solidity). Powers DeFi, NFTs, DAOs, tokens. Switched from Proof of Work to Proof of Stake in 2022 ("The Merge") — 99% less energy. Transaction fees ("gas") spike under load. Solana / Avalanche / Sui are alternative smart contract platforms.'),
    ('What is HIPAA?','US healthcare privacy law. PHI (Protected Health Information) must be encrypted at rest + in transit, access logged, BAA required with vendors, breach notification mandatory. Building healthcare apps: use HIPAA-compliant infrastructure (AWS, GCP, Azure offer compliant tiers); architect for least privilege.'),
    ('What is FHIR?','Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources. Modern standard for healthcare data exchange. REST + JSON resources (Patient, Observation, Medication, Encounter, etc.). Replaces legacy HL7 v2 (pipe-delimited messages). Use FHIR for new integrations. SMART on FHIR: launch web apps within EHRs with OAuth.'),
    ('What is Erlang?','Functional language designed for telephony. Fault tolerance + concurrency as primary goals. Runs on BEAM VM. Lightweight processes (millions per node), message passing only (no shared state), preemptive scheduling, hot code reload. Powers WhatsApp, Discord backend. Supervisor trees restart crashed processes.'),
    ('What is the let it crash philosophy?','Erlang/Elixir approach: don\'t defensively code for every edge case. Let processes crash; supervisor restarts them. Combined with isolation (no shared state), a crash doesn\'t corrupt others. Simpler code, more robust systems. Opposite of typical Java/Python defensive style.'),
    ('What is set -euo pipefail?','Bash strict mode flags. -e: exit on any unhandled error. -u: treat unset variables as error. -o pipefail: pipe fails if ANY command in chain fails (not just last). Together catch bugs early. Standard preamble for serious shell scripts. Add IFS=$\'\\n\\t\' to safely handle filenames with spaces.'),
    ('What is a HashMap?','Hash table data structure mapping keys to values. O(1) average get/put. Implementation: array of buckets, hash function picks bucket; collisions handled by chaining or open addressing. Java: HashMap (not thread-safe), ConcurrentHashMap (thread-safe). Python: dict. JS: Map. Resize when load factor exceeds threshold.'),
    ('What is LRU cache?','Least Recently Used cache. Bounded — evicts the entry not used for longest when capacity hit. Implementation: hash map + doubly-linked list, O(1) get and put. Python: functools.lru_cache decorator or collections.OrderedDict. Use for: memoization, query caches, anything with bounded working set.'),
    ('What is LinkedList?','Doubly-linked sequence — each node has prev + next pointers. Insert/delete at known node: O(1). Random access: O(n) (walk from head). Less cache-friendly than arrays. Java has LinkedList class; Python uses collections.deque (which is doubly-linked deque). Prefer ArrayList/vector unless mid-list inserts dominate.'),
    ('What is JSON?','JavaScript Object Notation. Text format for structured data. Six types: string, number, boolean, null, object, array. Lingua franca of web APIs. Parsed by every language. Caveats: no comments in strict JSON, no trailing commas, dates as strings, big ints lose JS precision. Alternatives: YAML (more human), Protobuf (binary, typed).'),
    ('What is YAML?','Human-readable data serialization format. Used heavily for config (Kubernetes, GitHub Actions, Ansible, docker-compose). Indentation-significant (like Python). Supports comments, multi-line strings, references (anchors). Gotchas: implicit type conversion ("yes"→true, "1.0"→float — surprising), whitespace bugs. Prefer JSON or TOML for new things unless YAML required by tooling.'),
    ('What is TOML?','Tom\'s Obvious Minimal Language. Config format more explicit than YAML, more readable than JSON. Used by: Rust (Cargo.toml), Python (pyproject.toml), Go (some tools). Tables, arrays, key-value. Strict typing. Good middle ground for human-edited config files.'),
    ('What is XML?','Extensible Markup Language. Verbose hierarchical data format. Tags + attributes. Used by: SOAP web services, RSS feeds, Office documents (docx is zipped XML), Android layouts, legacy enterprise systems. Mostly replaced by JSON for web APIs. Still pervasive in enterprise + document formats. Parsing libraries everywhere; pick streaming parser (SAX) for huge files.'),
    ('What is Protobuf?','Protocol Buffers — Google\'s binary serialization format. Define schema in .proto files; codegen generates parsers in many languages. Smaller + faster than JSON. Strongly typed. Used heavily for gRPC, Kafka messages, internal service comms. Trade-off: not human-readable in transit.'),
    ('What is Avro?','Binary serialization format from Apache. Schema embedded with data (no separate codegen step). Common in big data (Kafka, Hadoop, Spark). Schema evolution via reader/writer schemas (handles old + new readers). Pick Avro over Protobuf when you need self-describing data and schema evolution flexibility.'),
    ('What is Parquet?','Columnar storage format for analytics. Stores data by column instead of row → great compression + fast scans of subset of columns. Used by: Spark, BigQuery, DuckDB, Polars. Standard for data lake / lakehouse storage. Pair with Iceberg or Delta for transactions + schema evolution.'),
    ('What is gRPC?','RPC framework using HTTP/2 + Protocol Buffers. Strongly typed via .proto files; codegen generates client + server stubs. Supports unary, streaming. Faster + smaller than JSON over HTTP. Best for: service-to-service comms. Browser needs gRPC-Web (proxy). Use for backend; REST/GraphQL for browsers.'),
    ('What is WebSocket?','Bidirectional protocol over TCP. Persistent connection after HTTP upgrade. Binary or text frames. Use for: chat, multiplayer games, live updates, anything needing server-push. Modern alternative emerging: WebTransport (over QUIC, multiplexed streams). For one-way server push, SSE is simpler.'),
    ('What is SSE?','Server-Sent Events. Server-to-client only push over plain HTTP. Browser-native EventSource API. Auto-reconnect built in. Text-only. Use for: live feeds, notifications, dashboards. Simpler than WebSocket if you only need server → client push.'),
    ('What is OAuth 2.0?','Authorization framework. Lets users grant third-party apps limited access to their account WITHOUT sharing the password. User → resource owner → consents → owner gives app a TOKEN representing limited access. Token expires + can be revoked. OAuth is AUTHORIZATION; OIDC layer adds authentication.'),
    ('What is OpenID Connect?','OIDC — authentication layer on top of OAuth 2.0. Adds an ID token (JWT containing user identity claims) so the app KNOWS who the user is. "Sign in with Google" is OIDC. Use OIDC for user login flows.'),
    ('What is SAML?','Security Assertion Markup Language. XML-based protocol for SSO (single sign-on). Older than OIDC but still dominant in enterprise. User auths once with IdP (identity provider), IdP issues signed SAML assertion, SP (service provider) trusts it. Replaced by OIDC in modern apps. Configure once, debug XML signatures forever.'),
    ('What is SSO?','Single Sign-On. Auth once with identity provider; access many apps without re-entering credentials. Protocols: OIDC, SAML. Benefits: easier UX, centralized policy (revoke once = revoke everywhere), compliance. Cost: identity provider becomes critical infra (if down, nothing works).'),
    ('What is RBAC?','Role-Based Access Control. Assign users to roles; assign permissions to roles. User permissions = union of their roles\' permissions. Easy to reason about for small role sets. Limitations: role explosion with complex orgs; doesn\'t express data-attribute constraints (e.g., "can edit only own posts").'),
    ('What is ABAC?','Attribute-Based Access Control. Permissions evaluated by rules over attributes of user, resource, action, context. More flexible than RBAC. Example: "users in dept X can edit docs tagged Y when accessing from corp network." Tools: OPA (Open Policy Agent), Cedar (AWS). Steeper learning; pays off in complex orgs.'),
    ('What is Kafka?','Apache Kafka. Distributed streaming platform. Producers publish messages to topics; consumers subscribe. Messages persisted on disk (configurable retention), replicated across brokers. Partitioned topics scale horizontally. Used for: event streaming, log aggregation, microservice decoupling.'),
    ('What is RabbitMQ?','Mature message broker. AMQP protocol. Routing exchanges (direct, topic, fanout). Strong delivery guarantees + management UI. Compared to Kafka: better for traditional queueing (work distribution); Kafka better for replay + streaming + huge throughput. Use RabbitMQ for: task queues, RPC patterns.'),
    ('What is Redis?','In-memory data structure store. Key-value but with rich types: strings, hashes, lists, sets, sorted sets, streams, geo, hyperloglog. Sub-ms latency. Persistence options (RDB snapshots, AOF log). Use for: cache, session store, leaderboards, rate limiting, pub-sub, queues. Modern alternatives: Valkey (Redis fork), Dragonfly, KeyDB.'),
    ('What is PostgreSQL?','Open-source relational DB. ACID compliant, very feature-rich (JSON columns, full-text search, GIS, custom types, partial indexes, window functions, CTEs). De facto default for new projects. Scales to TBs + tens of thousands of QPS. Extensions: PostGIS (geo), pg_partman (partitioning), pgvector (embeddings), TimescaleDB (time series).'),
    ('What is MySQL?','Open-source relational DB. ACID via InnoDB engine. Massive ecosystem (most CMS/CRMs target it). Lighter than Postgres historically but feature parity improving. Used by: Facebook, YouTube, Wikipedia. Modern fork: MariaDB. Pick Postgres for new things unless ecosystem locks you in.'),
    ('What is MongoDB?','Document-oriented NoSQL. Stores JSON-like documents (BSON). Flexible schema. Horizontal scale via sharding. Good for: rapidly changing schemas, nested data, prototypes. Has transactions now (4.0+). Mature ecosystem (Atlas hosted). Often replaced by Postgres with JSONB columns for simpler architectures.'),
    ('What is SQLite?','Embedded SQL DB. No server — runs in process, reads/writes a single file. Tiny + fast. Used everywhere: phones (iOS, Android), browsers (Chrome history), apps (Mac\'s Calendar). Surprisingly capable — Litestream + Turso let you scale SQLite to multi-region. Default for prototypes and many production apps.'),
    ('What is Postgres?','See PostgreSQL. Open-source relational database. Default choice for most new projects. ACID, feature-rich, scales further than many think.'),
    ('What is React?','JavaScript library for building UIs. Component-based + declarative — describe UI as function of state. Virtual DOM diffs minimize real DOM ops. Hooks for state + effects in function components. Largest ecosystem of any frontend framework. Pair with Next.js for full-stack.'),
    ('What is Vue?','Progressive JS framework for UIs. Template-first (HTML-like) with reactivity. Vue 3 uses Composition API + <script setup>. Lighter learning curve than React. Strong in: rapid app dev, internal tools. Pair with Nuxt for full-stack.'),
    ('What is Svelte?','Compiler-first framework. Components compile to vanilla JS at BUILD time — no runtime virtual DOM. Smaller bundles, faster first paint. Reactivity = assignment. Pair with SvelteKit for full-stack (alternative to Next.js).'),
    ('What is Angular?','Google\'s full-fat frontend framework. TypeScript-first, opinionated structure, dependency injection, RxJS for async. Larger learning curve than React/Vue. Best for: large enterprise apps where structure matters more than minimalism. Less popular than React in recent years.'),
    ('What is Next.js?','React-based full-stack framework. SSR + SSG + ISR + client-side hydration. File-based routing, API routes, server components, edge runtime. De facto standard for new React apps. Compares to: SvelteKit, Nuxt, Remix. Use for: marketing sites, dashboards, e-commerce.'),
    ('What is Tailwind?','Utility-first CSS framework. Compose styles via class names: `<div class="flex items-center gap-2 p-4 bg-blue-500">`. Pros: no naming things, no jumping files, easy responsive. Cons: long class strings, smell of inline styles. Configurable via tailwind.config.js. Hugely popular for new projects.'),
    ('What is npm?','Node Package Manager. Default for JS package installation + project management. package.json describes project + deps. package-lock.json pins exact versions (commit it!). Modern alternatives: yarn (similar), pnpm (faster, hard-linked), bun (everything-fast). All compatible with npm registry.'),
    ('What is webpack?','Module bundler. Combines + transforms JS/CSS/assets into deployable bundles. Highly configurable but slow + complex. Modern projects: prefer Vite or esbuild. Webpack still everywhere in older codebases. Plugins for everything (loaders, transforms, optimizations).'),
    ('What is ESLint?','JavaScript linter. Catches bugs + enforces style. Configurable rule sets. Standard in modern JS projects. Pair with Prettier (formatter — no opinions, just consistency). Many frameworks ship default config (eslint-config-next, eslint-plugin-react).'),
    ('What is Prettier?','Opinionated code formatter for JS/TS/CSS/HTML/etc. Strips formatting decisions from devs — runs on save. Less bikeshedding. Pair with ESLint (linter). Black for Python; rustfmt for Rust. The future of code style is automation.'),
    ('What is sed?','Stream editor. Reads stdin/files line by line, applies edits, outputs. Most common: substitute. `sed "s/old/new/g" file`. -i edits in place. Powerful for batch text edits without writing scripts. Faster + lighter than Python for simple transformations.'),
    ('What is awk?','Field-oriented text processor. Splits each line into fields ($1, $2). Print column 2: `awk \'{print $2}\'`. Sum column 3: `awk \'{sum+=$3} END {print sum}\'`. Powerful for log analysis + tabular data manipulation without a real script.'),
    ('What is grep?','Pattern search in text. `grep "pattern" file`. -i case-insensitive, -r recursive, -v invert (show non-matching), -n line numbers, -A 3 / -B 3 / -C 3 (context), -l only file names. Modern: ripgrep (rg) — 10-100x faster, respects .gitignore.'),
    ('What is curl?','HTTP client CLI. Send any HTTP request, view response. `curl -X POST -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d \'{}\' url`. Used for: API testing, scripts, downloads. -v for verbose (see headers). -L follow redirects. Modern alternative for prettier output: httpie.'),
    ('What is jq?','Command-line JSON processor. Filter/transform JSON. `curl url | jq \'.items[] | select(.age > 30) | .name\'`. Indispensable for working with JSON APIs in shell scripts. Has its own query syntax (powerful + a learning curve).'),
    ('What is ssh?','Secure Shell. Encrypted remote terminal + file transfer. Public-key auth (preferred over passwords). `ssh user@host`. Tunneling via -L (local forward) / -R (remote). Config: ~/.ssh/config for aliases + per-host settings. Foundation of remote ops.'),
    ('What is tmux?','Terminal multiplexer. Multiple "windows" (tabs) + "panes" (splits) in one terminal. Detach + reattach (sessions survive disconnect). Use for: managing long-running tasks on remote servers, organized local workflows. Modern alternatives: zellij, screen (older). Critical skill for sysadmin/SRE.'),
    ('What is vim?','Modal text editor. Modes: normal (movement + commands), insert (typing), visual (selection), command (`:`). Steep learning curve; once learned, fast. Pre-installed on virtually every Unix system. Modern: Neovim (fork with Lua scripting + LSP). VSCode/JetBrains have vim emulation if you want the keybindings without the editor.'),
    ('What is GitHub Actions?','GitHub\'s built-in CI/CD. Define workflows in .github/workflows/*.yml. Triggers: push, PR, schedule, manual, etc. Runners: GitHub-hosted (free for public, generous for private) or self-hosted. Marketplace has thousands of pre-built actions. Standard for new open source + many teams.'),
    ('What is GitLab CI?','GitLab\'s built-in CI/CD. Define in .gitlab-ci.yml. Runs on GitLab\'s shared runners or self-hosted. Powerful: pipelines, parallelization, environments, schedules, manual approvals. Tightly integrated with GitLab repo. Top choice if you use GitLab for code.'),
    ('What is CircleCI?','SaaS CI/CD platform. Config in .circleci/config.yml. YAML-defined pipelines. Workflows + jobs + steps. Caching + parallelism + orbs (reusable config). Heavily used by JS/Python projects. Compare to GitHub Actions which has caught up significantly.'),
    ('What is Jenkins?','Old-school CI/CD platform. Self-hosted. Plugins for everything. Powerful but operational burden. Used in: enterprises, legacy projects. Modern projects: prefer GitHub Actions / GitLab CI / CircleCI for less ops.'),
    ('What is AWS?','Amazon Web Services. Largest cloud provider. Hundreds of services. Core: EC2 (VMs), S3 (object storage), RDS (managed databases), Lambda (serverless functions), ECS/EKS (containers), DynamoDB, IAM. Mature + sprawling. Steep learning. Industry default for many companies.'),
    ('What is GCP?','Google Cloud Platform. Strengths: data + ML (BigQuery, Vertex AI), networking, container orchestration (GKE — they invented Kubernetes). Generally cleaner UX than AWS. Slightly behind in raw service count. Use for: ML/data workloads, modern container-native apps.'),
    ('What is Azure?','Microsoft Azure. Strengths: enterprise integration (AD, Office), .NET ecosystem, Windows workloads. Massive presence in enterprise. UI legendarily worse than AWS/GCP (improving). Use for: orgs already using Microsoft stack.'),
    ('What is Cloudflare?','Edge / CDN + security platform. Workers for serverless at edge. R2 (S3-compatible storage, no egress fees). Pages for static + SSR sites. DNS + DDoS protection + WAF. Modern darling for edge-first apps. Pricing makes it attractive vs hyperscalers for many use cases.'),
    ('What is Vercel?','Hosting platform optimized for Next.js (they built it). Git-based deploys, preview branches, edge functions, image optimization. Great DX. Pricier than DIY for scale. Use for: Next.js apps, marketing sites, internal tools.'),
    ('What is Netlify?','Static + JAMstack hosting. Similar to Vercel; broader framework support. Build hooks, branch previews, edge functions, forms. Good for: static sites, JAMstack apps.'),
    ('What is Lambda?','AWS Lambda. Serverless functions. Pay per execution. No server management. Cold start latency (~100ms-1s) for less-frequent functions. Use for: event-driven workloads, glue code, low-traffic APIs. Compare: Cloud Functions (GCP), Azure Functions, Cloudflare Workers (faster cold start at edge).'),
]
